content:
@Joel "Roomie" Berghult shared this a while back 

“https://helpcenter.celemony.com/ is really good tbh, better than most first party learning resources

if you want a pop vocal workflow, Louis Bell shows his in his studio.com course

Love this thought and hear that completely. So funny enough, within the day or two after my original message, everybody was stoked about where we landed. And to your point about being patient, I think all we needed was a little more time to try stuff out and get on the same page. A good reminder not to sweat it too hard if I leave a session worried about the current state of the music. Putting it down for the evening and coming back with fresh ears does wonders. (Also should note that "arrangement decisions" was a massive oversimplification of the questions we were trying to answer lol).

Apologies if this turns into a novel, but would love to share some takeaways. I think the north star point you made is super important and well put. I think the artist I was working with got more comfortable trying new ideas the more he realized we were both aiming at the same thing (just approaching it differently). He's also only recorded / released one song before (and doesn't have much prior experience collaborating), so I totally understand the fear of things sounding different than he imagined. That's not a knock on the artist at all - I say that matter of factly and it's where everybody starts.

@NoahNeedleman made an analogy about being a "doctor vs a doula" which I found super insightful. I think I was afraid that trying to be a "doctor" at all was somehow inherently an ego move or underestimating the artist's instincts. Ended up concluding that the project required a little bit of both, and that it's 100% okay and helpful to know where my experience could help us reach the artist's intention. I think interpreting the artist's intention is so much of the job, and if they don't yet have the tools or experience, that may push our job a little more to the doctoring side. There was definitely still some doulaing of course.

Yeah I also feel like a lot of that vibe stemmed from latency issues and now that's just how they rap. Often I don't nudge a ton unless asked to cause it'll fuck up the flow and that's what these guys are kings of so 🤷‍♂️
// not sure about yachty's engineer. He just pulled up to the studio to do a feature with another artist I've been working with a lot. Was a cool experience. Maybe his engineer was just unavailable.
// done a bit with some of the less popular internet money guys and met taz once at a session but it's been a while since I've seen any of that crew

Thanks @philbarnes !

@Slow Hand I think just good sounds that I don't need to play with very much to get a vibe. 
Think co-write sessions with artists in the room, smash the drum pattern out in 10 minutes and then continue to work on the song without having to enter "Engineer" mode playing with plugins to make the drum sound passable.

@Beck Nebel I'm doing the same thing as Matt B. The techniques just broaden as one tries to reallllly lengthen a note.

This often happens when I'm doing a writing session and we do 30 mins of scrambling to record vocals at the end. I always get a lead where I realize after fact that a word should have been held out to match another word, or a part was sung out that should have been more staccato. 

And then I have to deliver an A+ sounding finished record (fuck a "demo"). So I use my whole bag of tricks to reallllly lengthen some shit. Many tools and tricks to use, and I can rarely be certain what will work best before I try them.
